  "prompt": "Why does a helicopter hover, but not move with constant velocity when there is no net force?",
  "response": "A helicopter hovers when the lift force generated by its rotor blades equals its weight, resulting in no net force acting on it. According to Newton's first law of motion, an object will remain at rest or move with constant velocity if there is no net force acting on it. \n\nWhen a helicopter is hovering, it is in a state of equilibrium, with no net force, so it remains at rest relative to the ground. If the pilot wants the helicopter to move with a constant velocity, they would need to tilt the rotor disk in the desired direction of motion, which creates a horizontal component of lift. This horizontal force would then accelerate the helicopter until the air resistance (drag) equals this force, resulting in a constant velocity. \n\nIn summary, a helicopter hovers and does not move with constant velocity when there is no net force because it is in a state of equilibrium, with the lift force equal to its weight. To move with constant velocity, a net force is required initially to overcome air resistance, after which the helicopter can maintain a constant velocity when the forces balance out again.",
